Introduction

The data provides ticket prices for one-way flights found on Expedia. We sought to find if seatsRemaining and totalTravelDistance affect the price of a plane ticket (totalFare) and used Multiple Linear Regression to do this. The original data is a 31GB file of flight tickets that range between 04/16/2022 and 10/05/2022.

Description of Variables

totalFare: Total price of ticket(USD)

seatsRemaining: Number of seats remaining

totalTravelDistance: Total travel distance in miles.

Statistical Analysis

We split the data set into 16 smaller files based on departing airport and randomly sampled 10% of the data. We used seatsRemaining and totalTravelDistance as predictors in all 16 models for basic economy tickets. Figure 1, shows the results we achieved from fitting the regression model for ATL airport.

Figure 1. Model of ATL

The linear regression model for Atlanta is as follows: \(totalFare = 71.35 + 3.68seatsRemaining + 0.06totalTravelDistance\)

For each seat remaining, holding distance constant, the ticket price will increase by about \(\$3.68\). For each 100 miles traveled, holding seats remaining constant, the ticket price will increase by about \(\$6\). Since the p-value for both coefficients is below \(\alpha = 0.05\), we can conclude that both seatsRemaining and totalTravelDistance affect ticket price.

The above plots are diagnostic plots before taking the 10% random sample. As seen, there are too many observations to get a good look at the underlying pattern. The below plots are after taking the 10% sample and unfortunately there are still so many observations but we did not want to lose the nature of the original data so we decided not to reduce the random sample further.

A weakness to our analysis is that we aren’t taking into consideration a temporal effect of ticket prices so holidays like Memorial Day, July 4th and Labor Day are treated the same as other days.

Comparing the 16 Models

The highest R-squared value of the 16 models is 43.82% and the lowest is 8.73%. These low values are most likely due to the temporal effect limitation discussed above. Nonetheless, both variables, seatsRemaining and totalTravelDistance, are significant in each model.

The coefficients for each of the 16 models vary. About half of the models have a negative relationship between seatsRemaining and totalFare, whereas the other half is positive. This could be due to an airline wanting to maximize revenue. For example, if a plane is not at full capcaity, they could charge more in order to make up for the seats that are vacant.

Condor Details

We created a shell script to split the large 31GB dataset, filtered by basic economy tickets, and removed unnecessary columns to reduce memory, leaving us with 16 files of size 20 to 30MB. Afterwards, we tested our R script by running a regression model on only one csv (ATL) to ensure our scripts were working before running them on all 16 files. We initially used 1GB of memory to run our first job but got an error message stating more memory was required to run the job. We increased our memory to 5GB but still failed. As a result we had to reduce our focus to only two factors. We realized that lm() requires a lot of memory to run in CHTC so increased our memory to 8GB to get just one job to run. Once our first job was successful, we ran three more jobs and then finally, ran all 16 jobs which took about 6 minutes to run in total and required 20GB of memory along with 2GB of disk space.

Since linear regression requires a lot of memory to run in CHTC, it may not be the best option when there are a hundred jobs to run. It was also hard to view visualizations on CHTC. The only way to view plots was by transferring the files to our local machine which can be time consuming when there are multiple jobs to run.

Conclusion

Based on our analysis, seatsRemaining and totalTravelDistance significantly impact the price of a plane ticket regardless of the 16 departing airports we analyzed. For future analysis we could add the temporal effect of the ticket since we did not look at that aspect for this analysis.
